Got it üëç ‚Äî just to clarify: when you say ‚ÄúJava using portfolio‚Äù, do you mean you want an example of a Java program (console-based or GUI) that displays a portfolio, or are you asking for JavaScript (since it‚Äôs commonly used with HTML/CSS for portfolios)?


---

‚úÖ If you meant JavaScript (for web portfolio)

Here‚Äôs how you can add interactivity to your existing HTML + CSS portfolio.

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>My Portfolio</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>

  <header>
    <h1>My Portfolio</h1>
    <nav>
      <a href="#about">About</a>
      <a href="#projects">Projects</a>
      <a href="#contact">Contact</a>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <section id="about">
    <h2>About Me</h2>
    <p>Hello! I'm a web developer passionate about creating modern websites.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="projects">
    <h2>My Projects</h2>
    <article>
      <h3>Project 1</h3>
      <p>A project description.</p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>Project 2</h3>
      <p>Another project description.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section id="contact">
    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>Email: example@email.com</p>
    <button id="changeBg">Change Background</button>
  </section>

  <footer>
    <p>&copy; 2025 My Portfolio</p>
  </footer>

  <!-- JavaScript -->
  <script>
    // Change background color on button click
    document.getElementById("changeBg").addEventListener("click", function() {
      const colors = ["#1e1e2f", "#2c3e50", "#4a148c", "#00695c", "#b71c1c"];
      const randomColor = colors[Math.floor(Math.random() * colors.length)];
      document.body.style.backgroundColor = randomColor;
    });
  </script>

</body>
</html>


